summary.seg: The manuscript contains a text on geometry, Euclid's Elements . The work is not in its complete form: Ff.3.32 contains only the statements of the propositions.

The text was written in the 16th century by the Greek scribe Angelos Bergikios (Ange Vergèce, first quarter of 16th c.-1569). Born in Crete, from 1539 he worked in Paris, where he was appointed scriptor of the Royal Library in Fontainebleau.

The scribe copied this same text in another codex, MS Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale, Suppl. gr. 186 (ff. 1r-78r), completed by him, according to its colophon, in Rome in 1537. The Paris manuscript shows geometrical diagrams which are not present in MS Ff.6.32.

msItem.author: Euclid
msItem.title: Elements
msItem.incipit: f. 2r Στοιχείων τὸ πρῶτον. Σημεῖον ἐστίν, οὗ μέρος οὐθέν.
msItem.explicit: f. 75r Εἰς τὸ δοθὲν εἰκοσάεδρον δωδεκάεδρον ἐγγράψαι.
msItem.note: The text contains only the statements of the propositions, numbered for each book
The sequence of the propositions does not always match that of the edition (post L. Heiberg ed. E.S. Stamatis, Euclidis Elementa, 1-5, Leipzig 1969-19772)
For book 14 the propositions end with no. 6 of the edition (ed. Heiberg-Stamatis vol. 5.1, p. 10 linn. 1-3), which in the manuscript in numbered δ΄ (4)

list.item: ff. 73r-75r Book 14 (book 14 of Euclid's Elements is considered spurious and is attributed to Hypsicles, of Alexandria Hypsicles of Alexandria )

support.material: ff. 1-82 Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermark: Two arrows surmounted by a six pointed star ( ca. 76 ca. 35 ) near the upper edge, links comparable to Harlfinger, Flèche 19 which is dated to 1534-1536.

foliation.p: Modern foliation in pencil, in Arabic numerals, in the top right hand corner, recto: 1-82
The main scribe wrote running heads in red ink in the upper margin of each verso Βιβλίον, and in the upper margin of each recto, where he indicates the book number.

supportDesc.condition: There is a tear on the lower margin of f. 1r. Humidity and water stains are found throughout the volume, particularly in the upper margins of the leaves, near the gutter (s. e.g. ff. 69v-70r), in some leaves also in the lower margin (s. e.g. ff.40v-41r). Brown and orange stains on f. 1r and on the right pastedown .

handNote.p: The text was written by Vergece, Ange, 1505 - 1569 Angelos Bergikios (Ἄγγελος Βεργίκιος, 16th c., first quarter-1569, RGK I, 3; on the scribe see also RGK II, 3; RGK III, 3) in an elegant and accurate minuscule script, with "baroque" features, slanting slightly to the right. The script shows many ligatures and ornamental features, such as curling flourishes at the strokes' end.
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials in red.
The scribe also wrote additions to the text in the margins.

Hand a: a hand datable to the 16th c. added two marginal notes in brown ink. The script is an informal minuscule, slanting to the right, with regular features, probably by a western European hand. It appears to be the same hand that wrote ff. 36r and vii recto in MS Cambridge, University Library, Kk.5.31

decoDesc.decoNote: Initials in ekthesis in red ink are decorated with a vegetal motif with scrollworks, see e.g. f. 2r.
Thick minor initials written in red ink see e.g. f. 6r.
Pearls and small crosses in brown and red ink are traced at the end of the prepositions and of books, see e.g. f. 10r. Small crosses in brown ink are present in the upper margins of all leaves.

additions.p: On the left pastedown, in pencil, letter G, a modern annotation by a librarian.
On f. 1v there is a title, Euclidis geometria by a hand recurring in the manuscripts owned by J.-B. Hautin (see Provenance).
On ff. 21r-22v, in the left margin, the definitions of Book 5 are numbered in Arabic numerals from 1 to 20 in brown ink. Judging by the ink, it could be an addition by Hand a.

binding.p: Modern binding. Paper over couched-laminate boards. Spine covered in leather, tooled in gold with title Euclid M.S.; leather labels with the shelfmark are pasted on it. 175 110 18

origin.p: The manuscript was written by the Greek scribe Angelos Bergikios (16th c., first quarter-1569). It is not dated. The same type of watermark found in this manuscript recurs also in MS Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale, gr. 1836, which was copied by Bergikios in Venice in 1536 (see the description of the manuscript by J. Groisard (2006-2009), in BnF, Archives et manuscrits). Moreover, Bergikios copied the same text contained in MS Ff.6.32 in the MS Par. Suppl. gr. 186, completed in Rome in 1537. Therefore it is probable that also this manuscript was written around the 1530s.

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by a certain J.B. Hautin, probably to be identified with Jean Baptiste II Hautin, son of the French scholar and numismatist Haultin, Jean-Baptiste, approximately 1580-1640 Jean-Baptiste Hautin (ca. 1580-1640) : on f. 1v there is a title by the hand, which occurs in almost all Hautin's manuscripts: Euclidis geometria (see Jackson 2006, p. 33 no. 5).

It passed afterwards to John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : number 1043 in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now MS Oo.7.50(2), compiled by Thomas Tanner (1674-1735) after the publication of C. Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697) (see also McKitterick 1986, p. 142, and Jackson 2006, p. 33 no. 5).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . On f. 1v is glued the engraved bookplate made by John Pine for the Royal Library (1737).

recordHist.source: Description (2019) draws partly on A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 2, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1857, p. 534.
